\begin_layout Title
The Maximum Circular Velocity Dependence of Halo Clustering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
We study dependence of halo clustering on the maximum circular velocity
 (hereafter, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

), which is a measure of their potential well depth of halos and is tightly
 connected to the feedback efficiency for galaxy formation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
In this study, we measure halo bias through two-point correlation functions
 for halos split into high 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 and low 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 samples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
At constant halo mass, we see residual dependence of halo clustering on
 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

.
 In low mass regime, high-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos cluster more strongly than low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos; at 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}\thickapprox10^{11.6}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, the linear bias for high-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos is 
\begin_inset Formula $40\%$
\end_inset

 larger.
 In high mass regime, this trend reverses that low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

halos cluster more strongly, and the overall difference is smaller.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $r<10h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

, halo bias for high-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos exhibit significantly different scale-dependent feature compared
 to the bias for low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos; high-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos cluster strongly at 
\begin_inset Formula $1h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 and their clustering signal differs by 60% at 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}\approx10^{11.8}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 compared to their low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

counterparts.
 This scale-dependent feature, however, is significantly reduced by excluding
 ejected halos from the samples.
 The ejected halos are the halos which are identified as host halos at present
 epoch but were subhalos of more massive host halos in the past, and they
 are known to host satellite galaxies instead of central galaxies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
As possible observational consequences of the results, we relate an observable
 property of a galaxy (luminosity, stellar mass) to an intrinsic property
 of its host halo (mass, circular velocity).
 By using different choices for the halo property, we see a clear scale
 dependence in clustering at 
\begin_inset Formula $1h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

, with a maximum difference of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim15\%$
\end_inset

.
 These differences go down to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim5\%$
\end_inset

 after removing the ejected halos.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
The halo model provides a connection between dark matter halos and galaxies,
 and it has been remarkably successful in describing observations of galaxy
 clustering.
 In particular,
\color inherit
 the Halo Occupation Distribution (HOD) and the Conditional Luminosity Function
 (CLF) are the two most widely used models of the galaxy-halo connection.
 Those models assume that halo mass completely determines the galaxy occupation
 statistics.
 In order to populate halos with galaxies, the HOD gives the probability
 
\begin_inset Formula $P(N|M)$
\end_inset

 that a halo with mass 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{M}$
\end_inset

 hosts 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 galaxies, while the CLF models the mean abundance 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi(L|M)$
\end_inset

 of galaxies with luminosity 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 which live in a dark matter halo of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Those two models are convertible because they operate under the same assumption
; we can obtain an HOD by integrating the CLF against luminosity and a CLF
 by differentiating the HOD with respect to luminosity.
 Both models have been applied extensively to observations in order to study
 the halo-galaxy connection [
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "magliocchetti03,zehavi05a,yang_etal05,zheng07,vdBosch07,zheng09,skibba09,simon_etal09,ross10,zehavi11,geach12,parejko13"

\end_inset

] as well as cosmology [
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tinker05,leauthaud11b,more_etal13,cacciato_etal13,mandelbaum13"

\end_inset

].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The halo clustering in large N-body simulations, however, exhibits dependence
 on additional halo properties besides halo mass [
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gao_etal05,wechsler06,gao_white07,li_etal08"

\end_inset

].
 This additional dependence is known as halo assembly bias; halos of the
 same mass in different environment have different assembly history and
 cluster differently.
 Having different assembly history also affects to the internal structure
 of halos.
 If galaxy formation is tightly connected to the internal structure of halos
 and its assembly history, galaxy clustering will have assembly bias.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a response to halo assembly bias, a recent trend in connecting halos
 and galaxies has been to use the Abundance Matching technique [
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kravtsov04a,vale_ostriker04,tasitsiomi_etal04,vale_ostriker06,conroy_wechsler09,guo10,simha10,neistein11a,watson_etal12b,rod_puebla12,kravtsov13"

\end_inset

], which assumes a monotonic relation in size of galaxies and halos in order
 to assign galaxies to halos in a hierarchical manner.
 In order to evaluate size of halos, the maximum circular velocity, which
 is a measure of potential well depth of halos, is often used due to its
 tight correlation with stellar mass of galaxies.
 In the Abundance Matching technique, halo assembly bias is a generic prediction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Besides halo assembly bias, there have been several studies discussing definitio
n of a more physically motivated boundary for halos.
 A virial radius of halos is commonly used as a boundary definition.
 Those studies, however, show that halos and their environmental effects
 extend well beyond the virial radius and a more physically motivated boundary
 is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

splashback
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 radius at which splashback material generates a caustic [
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "diemer14,adhikari14,wetzel_nagai14,more15"

\end_inset

].
 The environmental effects of halos beyond their virial radius is also found
 in galaxy groups and clusters; galaxies which are beyond the virial radius
 of groups/clusters tend to have more quiescent star formation rates [
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wetzel_etal13"

\end_inset

].
 Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wetzel_etal13"

\end_inset

 shows that it is due to ejected satellite galaxies which orbit beyond their
 host halo's virial radius and eventually fall back in.
 Those ejected satellite galaxies live in ejected halos, which were within
 the virial radius of more massive host halos in the past but identified
 as a distinguished halo at present epoch.
 Since those ejected halos host very different type of galaxies than central
 galaxies that host halos host, it is crucial to understand the effect of
 ejected halos on halo clustering.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper, we explore the additional dependence of galaxy clustering
 on the central velocity dispersion both on small and large scales.
 In Section 2, we briefly describe the simulations, halo finding algorithm,
 and identification of halo types.
 In Section 3, we explore halo clustering as a function of halo mass and
 the maximum circular velocity through two-point correlation functions.
 We also investigate the effect of ejected halos on the halo clustering.
 In Section4, we show how the Abundance Matching techniques based on halo
 mass and the maximum circular velocity make qualitatively different predictions
 for the clustering of central galaxies to connect our findings in Section
 3 to observations.
 In Section 5, we discuss the implications of our results and summarize
 our main conclusions.
\end_layout

