\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper, we explore additional dependence of halo clustering on the
 maximum circular velocity of halos in addition to halo mass.
 The maximum circular velocity is a measure of potential well depth of halos,
 which determines the escape velocity of particles around the halos and
 therefore determines the feedback efficiency for galaxy formation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we measure linear bias for high/low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}>10^{12.8}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos cluster more strongly than high-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos.
 This is nicely explained in terms of the statistics of peaks and peak curvature
 of random Gaussian fields [
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dalal_etal08"

\end_inset

].
 Two halos with the same mass originated from the same peak height but different
 peak curvature cluster differently because of their different environment.
 Halos with shallower peak curvature, which end up to be low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos, tend to live in high density region and therefore cluster more strongly.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}<10^{12.8}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, high-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos cluster more strongly than low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos, and the difference in linear bias increases up to 
\begin_inset Formula $40\%$
\end_inset

 with decreasing halo mass.
 On low mass regime, mass growth of halos are affected by tidal field; high-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos are the ones whose mass growth is suppressed by strong tidal field
 generated in high-density region [
\color red

\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wang_etal11,shi15"

\end_inset


\color black
].
 
\color inherit
Our result for linear bias is consistent with previous studies investigating
 clustering dependence on other parameters such as formation time and concentrat
ion [
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gao_etal05,wechsler06,gao_white07,li_etal08"

\end_inset

].
 Due to a tight correlation between 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 and those parameters, this agreement is expected.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
Next, we explore the scale dependence of halo bias at 
\begin_inset Formula $r<10h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

.
 Halo bias for high-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos show non-trivial scale dependence with a bump at 
\begin_inset Formula $1h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 compared to the bias for low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos.
 This scale dependence feature for high-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos becomes 60% larger compared to low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos at 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}\approx10^{11.7}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
 This feature, however, is removed by excluding the ejected halos.
 By definition, the ejected halos are physically associated with a more
 massive halo.
 Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wetzel_etal13"

\end_inset

 shows that those ejected halos are subhalos which are gravitationally bound
 to more massive host halos beyond the virial radius of those host halos
 and eventually fall into the host halos after a few Gyrs.
 Those ejected halos host satellite galaxies having more quiescent star
 formation rate than a central galaxy.
 Their clustering signal is therefore determined by this associated halo,
 much like the clustering of subhalos is determined by its host halo.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
In Section 4, we demonstrate that abundance matching techniques, which relate
 an observable property of a galaxy (luminosity, stellar mass) to an intrinsic
 property of its host halo (mass, circular velocity), give a very different
 scale dependence on halo bias at 
\begin_inset Formula $r<10h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

; we see a clear scale dependence in clustering at 
\begin_inset Formula $1h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

, with a maximum difference of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim15\%$
\end_inset

 with the ejected halos and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim5\%$
\end_inset

 without the ejected halos.
 Since this scale-dependence correlates strongly with whether the host halo
 samples selected by halo mass or maximum circular velocity, we can possibly
 test whether a stellar mass of a galaxy is tightly correlated with one
 of those two parameters in observations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One interesting question we did not explore in this paper is whether those
 ejected halos are within the splashback radius of more massive host halos,
 which is the radius where accreted matter reaches its first apocenter of
 orbit after turnaround.
 Several studies, which explore a more physically motivated definition of
 halo radius, propose the idea of the splashback radius [
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "diemer14,adhikari14,wetzel_nagai14,more15"

\end_inset

].
 If all the ejected halos are within the splashback radius of host halos,
 we will have more motivation to use splashback radius as a halo radius
 and we do not need to consider treating the ejected halos differently since
 they are naturally within the halo boundary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary, we found a consistent trend with previous works in additional
 dependence of linear bias on the maximum circular velocity for both high/low
 mass halos.
 We also found that scale dependence of halo assembly bias on small scales
 mostly come from the ejected halos.
\end_layout

